{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1020"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1020"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.63,0.08,0.02,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68082"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1020"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53539"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"9133"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents with a six-month history of intermittent painless rectal bleeding. The bleeding only occurs at the time of defaecation and is most noticeable if he has been constipated. It is not mixed within the stool and is present on wiping. He has no other health issues. Family history is negative for colorectal carcinoma. On perianal inspection and when bearing down, no external or prolapsing internal haemorrhoids are found. Digital rectal examination is unremarkable and anoscopy shows haemorrhoids that bulge into the anal canal. Complete blood count is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important plan of investigation or management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance alone","Dietary modification and reassessment","Rubber Band Ligation","Injection sclerotherapy","Colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlthough this patient has a clear history of outlet bleeding with no risk factors for cancer and examination findings of haemorrhoids, based on his age (\u0026gt;50 years) he should have an endoscopic evaluation of his colon to exclude malignancy. Although most patients with haematochezia will not have colorectal cancer, it is important to investigate this diagnosis in this age group. Therefore this patient (in addition to dietary advice), should have a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Efor further evaluation.  In patients with rectal bleeding \u0026gt;40 years, there is a move towards also performing a colonoscopy as 1 in 10 patients have been found to have neoplastic polyps. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs part of the assessment it is important to ascertain a history of red flag symptoms (eg, iron deficiency anaemia, constitutional symptoms, unexplained abdominal pain, altered bowel habit) and a family history of colon cancer, which would indicate the need to perform a colonoscopy at a younger age. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has grade I internal haemorrhoids (bulge without prolapse on valsalva). With respect to management of his haemorrhoids, \u003Cstrong\u003Edietary modification\u003C/strong\u003E (adequate fluid and fibre) and counselling on defecation habits is first-line management. If this fails, then office based procedures such as \u003Cstrong\u003Erubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E (most effective) or \u003Cstrong\u003Einjection sclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance alone\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as these haemorrhoids may continue to worsen given his history of straining. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haematochezia in patients \u003E50 years old should be investigated with colonoscopy"],"references":["Davis BR, Lee-Kong SA, Migaly J, et al. The American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Haemorrhoids. Diseases of the Colon and Rectum 2018. 61(3): 284-92. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29420423/","Koh FH, Seah A, Chan D, Tan KK. Is Colonoscopy indicated in young patients with hematochezia. Gastrointestinal Tumors 2017; 4(3-4): 90-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29594110/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53539"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1020"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53539"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T22:30:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T22:30:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1020"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoj